The usual way to validate a model is to consider the goodness-of-fit using the linear regression coefficients, R2. However, using only the linear regression method may not be appropriate for comparing the goodness of fit of kinetic models. This is because an occurrence of the inherent bias resulting from linearization may affect the deduction. Therefore, in this study in addition to the linear regression analysis, the experimental data were tested with sum-of-square error (Ferror) [30] to determine the best fitting kinetic model. The error function is given by (Eq. (5)):5Ferror=∑(Qe,calc-Qe,exp)2N2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F_{\text{error} } = \sqrt[2]{\sum{\frac{{({ Q_{\text{e} ,\text{calc} } - Q_{\text{e} , \exp } })^2 }}{ N}}}$$\end{document}where Qe,exp is the experimentally determined sorption capacity; Qe,calc is the theoretical sorption capacity from the different kinetic models and N is the number of data points.

